===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|bad|lang=enm}}, {{term|badde||wicked, evil, depraved|lang=enm}}, probably a shortening of {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|bæddel||hermaphrodite|lang=ang}} (cf. English {{term|much|lang=en}}, {{term|wench}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|myċel}}, {{m|ang|wenċel}}), from {{term|bædan||to defile|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*bad-}} (cf. Old High German {{term|pad||hermaphrodite|lang=goh}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰoidʰ}}- (cf. Welsh {{term|baedd||wild boar|lang=cy}}, Latin {{term|foedus||foul, filthy|lang=la}}, {{m|la|foedō||to defile, pollute}}).

